# SEQUENCE I - THE LAST MORNING

FADE IN:

INT. SOLOMON'S HOUSE - PRE-DAWN

A kettle begins to whistle. MALIK OKU, 36, appears from the pantry in funeral trousers and a white undershirt. He crosses the kitchen before the whistle reaches its full voice. Switches off the burner.

Checks the other three. All cold. The house around him is ready for a man who will not come downstairs. At the entrance: A polished pair of black shoes. A carved walking stick.

Prayer beads looped carefully over the handle. In the living room: ACHEBE beside SOYINKA. An EFIK BIBLE with a repaired spine. Canadian immigration manuals, decades out of date.

A brass leopard on a tray darkened by fingerprints. Family photographs arranged with almost obsessive care. One frame hangs crooked. The only one. In the kitchen: Gari. Crayfish. Maggi. Peak Milk. Ovaltine.

Three mustard jars in the refrigerator door. One thriving plant on the sill. Two dead ones beside it. Malik pours hot water into a mug. Does not drink. He wipes an already-clean section of counter. Stops.

Looks toward the staircase. Nothing there but the pale square of the landing. The front door opens. ADE OKU, 32, enters carrying his dress shoes. His tie hangs around his neck like a surrender flag.

He watches Malik wipe the same place again.

ADE
You know they sell those pre-cleaned.

MALIK
You said six-thirty.

ADE
I meant emotionally.

Malik checks his watch. 6:41. Then the wall clock. 6:40.

ADE
Vancouver is running behind.

Malik watches the second hand. It hesitates at twelve. Moves. Hesitates again. He takes the clock down and removes the battery. The ticking stops.

ADE
You won.

MALIK
It is broken.

ADE
That has never stopped you before.

Malik sets the clock face-down. Three coffees wait beside the sink in a straight line. Ade takes the one at the end. Malik moves the remaining two closer together. Ade notices. He opens the refrigerator. Yellow mustard.

Dijon. Grainy. Ade rests his thumb on the grainy lid. Closes the refrigerator without taking anything.

MALIK
You need to change.

ADE
This is black.

MALIK
Those are sweatpants.

ADE
Grief has lowered its standards.

Malik removes a loose thread from Ade's coat sleeve. Ade lets him. The front door opens again. KAI OKU, 25, enters with a digital camera against his chest and noise-cancelling headphones around his neck.

He stops just inside. Listens. The refrigerator hum. Water moving through old pipes. A delivery truck reversing two houses away. The soft scrape of Malik folding a dish towel into exact thirds.

Kai looks toward the face-down clock.

KAI
What happened to it?

MALIK
It loses time.

Kai turns the clock face-up. The missing battery rests beside it.

KAI
One second every minute.

ADE
Dad bought it at a gas station.

KAI
He hated losing time.

MALIK
Then he should have bought a better clock.

Malik picks up his mug. Still does not drink. Near Solomon's chair sits an old CAMCORDER. Scratched casing. A strip of masking tape underneath: SOLOMON. Kai picks it up.

Presses POWER. Nothing. He opens the battery compartment. Empty.

KAI
Where is the battery?

MALIK
Leave it.

KAI
He kept them in the blue drawer.

Kai crosses to a narrow drawer beside the telephone. Opens it. Rubber bands. Receipts. A tiny screwdriver. Three dead pens. No battery. Kai searches beneath the receipts.

MALIK
Kai.

Kai closes the drawer. Then opens it again.

ADE
Maybe it achieved freedom.

Kai keeps searching.

ADE
The battery. Not Dad.

No one laughs. Ade looks down. Kai removes every object from the drawer and arranges them on the counter. Rubber bands together. Pens parallel. Receipts by size. One receipt is folded around something hard.

Kai opens it. A small BRASS CARVING. Worn smooth at the edges. Animal at one angle. Mask at another. Kai turns it beneath the kitchen light.

MALIK
Put it back.

KAI
What is it?

MALIK
Something he kept.

KAI
That is not an answer.

MALIK
It is this morning.

Kai studies Malik. Sets the carving beside the camcorder. Malik returns it to the receipt. Returns the receipt to the drawer. Closes the drawer firmly. Kai crosses to the crooked photograph.

The three brothers as children beside Solomon. Malik rigid in a suit too large for him. Ade caught halfway through saying something. Kai small enough to be held. Solomon looks directly at the camera. Not smiling.

The frame leans slightly left. Kai straightens it. Steps back. The ceiling light washes Solomon's face from the glass. Kai tilts the frame crooked again. Solomon returns.

KAI
He did that on purpose.

MALIK
Did what?

KAI
Left it wrong.

ADE
Maybe he was testing whether Malik could feel joy.

Malik lifts three garment bags.

MALIK
Get dressed.

Kai remains by the photographs. On a lower shelf, an empty rectangle interrupts a line of dust. Something stood there long enough to leave an outline.

KAI
What is missing?

Malik checks the folder he brought. Funeral programme. Death certificate. Three printed schedules.

MALIK
Nothing we need today.

KAI
That is not what I asked.

MALIK
We leave in twelve minutes.

ADE
He made an agenda for Dad's funeral.

MALIK
Someone had to.

ADE
Yeah.

Too fast. Too sharp. Malik looks at him. Ade softens.

ADE
Imagine the chaos otherwise. People grieving without assigned seating.

Malik aligns the folder with the counter's edge.

ADE
There he is.

MALIK
Who?

ADE
Nobody.

Ade takes the garment bags from him. For one brief moment, Malik has nothing in his hands. He looks toward the staircase. The three brothers follow his gaze. The landing is empty. Solomon's bedroom door stands open.

Malik turns away first. On the dining table, the BRASS URN waits beside a vase of white flowers.

Smaller than the silence around it. Malik lifts it. Tests the lid. Once. Again. A faint thumbprint marks the polished brass. He wipes it with his sleeve. The print smears. He wipes harder.

ADE
Malik.

Malik stops. Ade holds out both hands.

ADE
Let me.

Malik looks at the hands. Then at Ade.

MALIK
Take the flowers.

Ade leaves his hands there for another beat. Then takes the vase. Kai switches off the kitchen light. Dawn does the rest. The brothers move toward the door: Ade with flowers and garment bags.

Kai with his camera and the funeral programmes. Malik with their father. Before Kai leaves, he looks back at the crooked photograph. He does not straighten it. The front door closes.

CUT TO:

# SEQUENCE II - THE FUNERAL

EXT. MOUNTAIN VIEW CEMETERY - MEMORIAL LAWN - MORNING

Rain hangs in the air without committing to a drop. A white canopy has been raised among cedars. Beneath it: Folding chairs. White flowers. A framed photograph of Solomon. The brass urn at the center. No grave.

A small Nigerian choir sings beside a portable speaker. The sound is beautiful until the speaker dries it into static. Mourners fill the chairs.

Black Canadian wool beside Nigerian formal wear. Old friends from church. Former patients from Solomon's clinic. Neighbours who knew the shape of his car better than the shape of his life.

The brothers stand in the front row. Malik nearest the urn. He has folded the programme into a perfect rectangle. Ade receives condolences with both hands. He gives each person the response they need.

KAI stands half a step behind them. His camera hangs unused. The OFFICIANT reads from the repaired Efik Bible.

OFFICIANT
We return Solomon Oku to the keeping
of those who loved him, and we ask
for mercy upon what remains unfinished.

Malik's eyes move to the order of service. Final prayer. Hymn. Family departure. He checks that the choir is ready before the officiant has finished speaking. The choir leader raises one hand. The microphone SHRIEKS.

Ordinary feedback. Metallic and sudden. Everyone flinches. Kai folds around the sound. One hand clamps over his right ear. The choir, the rain, the murmuring crowd - all of it collapses into a thin electrical ring.

The officiant's mouth keeps moving. No words reach him. Ade sees. He steps close enough for Kai to feel him.

ADE
Kai.

Kai watches Ade's lips.

ADE
Look at me.

Kai does. Ade breathes slowly. Kai matches him. The speaker is switched off. The ringing recedes. Sound returns in pieces: Shoes shifting on wet grass. Someone coughing into a handkerchief.

The choir continuing without amplification. Malik turns at last.

MALIK
You all right?

KAI
It was loud.

MALIK
I know.

Kai looks at Ade. Ade holds his gaze. At the rear of the canopy, a man waits beside a small travel bag. BODE OKU, 64. Solomon's younger brother.

Rain has darkened the shoulders of his coat. An airline tag still circles the handle of his bag. He arrived too late to hide how far he came. He does not interrupt. He removes his cap for the final prayer.

Malik sees him. Something in Malik's posture hardens before it gives way. The prayer ends. The choir's last note thins beneath the canopy. People rise. Condolences begin moving toward the brothers.

Bode waits until the oldest church women have passed. Then he approaches. He looks at Malik first.

BODE
Malik.

Malik takes his uncle's hand. Bode draws him into a brief, private embrace. He greets Ade. Then Kai.

Kai feels the travel still in Bode's coat: rain, recycled air, a trace of cologne applied in another time zone. Bode looks at the urn. Then back to Malik.

BODE
Was it peaceful?

Malik answers without looking away.

MALIK
Yes.

Ade lowers his eyes. Kai studies Malik. Bode waits. Malik does not revise the answer.

BODE
Good.

A beat.

ADE
You made it.

BODE
Your father spent seventeen years
accusing me of being late.

ADE
Was he right?

BODE
Only when somebody else was waiting.

Bode looks at the photograph beside the urn.

BODE
At sixteen, he missed the school bus
and ran behind it with his shoes in
his hands.

KAI
Why was he not wearing them?

BODE
He said shoes made a man slow.

ADE
Dad said that?

BODE
Your father had many beliefs before
he had responsibilities.

Ade laughs. One clean breath of it. Even Malik almost does. The FUNERAL DIRECTOR approaches with respectful distance.

FUNERAL DIRECTOR
Mr. Oku. Whenever your family is ready,
you may take the urn.

Malik moves before anyone else can. He gathers the urn against his chest. Ade reaches for the flowers. Bode watches the order settle into place.

FUNERAL DIRECTOR
The reception room is through the
south doors.

MALIK
Thank you.

Malik takes one step. His grip tightens. The urn slips less than an inch. His entire body reacts. Bode puts one hand beneath the base. Malik does not release it. Bode does not pull.

They stand like that while mourners move around them.

MALIK
I have it.

BODE
I know.

Malik's fingers whiten against the brass.

MALIK
I'm trying not to make another mistake
for him.

Bode keeps his hand beneath the urn.

BODE
Give me one side.

Malik looks at his uncle's hand. Then shifts his grip enough to make space. Bode takes half the weight. They carry Solomon toward the reception room together. Ade follows with the flowers.

Kai picks up Bode's travel bag.

INT. MOUNTAIN VIEW CEMETERY - RECEPTION ROOM - LATER

Condensation clouds the windows. Coats steam on chair backs. Jollof rice, meat pies, fried plantain, tea. Solomon's brass urn rests where Malik can see it from anywhere in the room.

Mourners contradict one another over the man he was. A woman tells Ade he has Solomon's laugh. Ade thanks her. For the rest of the reception, he smiles without showing his teeth. Malik keeps one hand on the back of the chair nearest the urn.

Kai stops at a photograph on the memorial table. Three young people outside a weathered house: SOLOMON, lean and unsmiling. BODE, younger, one hand raised against the sun. A GIRL between them.

Her face has been scratched away. Not crossed out with ink. Cut from the emulsion with a sharp point, stroke after deliberate stroke. Kai tilts the photograph. The grooves catch the fluorescent light.

Ade steps in beside him. His social smile disappears.

ADE
That was done on purpose.

In the background of the photograph, a brass object rests on the veranda wall. Too small to identify. The same compact silhouette as the carving in Solomon's blue drawer. Bode steps into the edge of their silence.

He sees the photograph. His face settles.

KAI
Who was she?

BODE
Someone your father loved badly.

ADE
Did he do this?

BODE
Not here.

Bode glances at two mourners close enough to hear. Malik joins them.

MALIK
What is it?

Kai gives him the photograph. Malik reads the damage before he reads the people.

BODE
Solomon's lawyer will come to the
house tomorrow morning.

MALIK
Why?

BODE
The will.

MALIK
You know what is in it.

BODE
Solomon left instructions. They are
for his sons.

Malik looks from the scratched face to the urn.

EXT. MOUNTAIN VIEW CEMETERY - PARKING AREA - AFTERNOON

The rain finally commits. Bode and Malik carry the urn between them beneath one umbrella. The umbrella is too small. Ade walks ahead to open the car.

Kai follows with Bode's travel bag and the scratched photograph protected inside his coat. At the back door, Bode offers to take the urn completely. Malik considers it.

MALIK
One side.

Bode nods. Together, they place Solomon inside.

CUT TO:

# SEQUENCE III - THE WILL AND DECISION

INT. SOLOMON'S HOUSE - DINING ROOM - MORNING

The flowers from the funeral have begun to open. The urn stands on the sideboard. The damaged photograph lies face-up on the dining table. Beside it: The brass carving from the blue drawer.

Kai has brought the two objects together. MAYA PATEL, 48, Solomon's estate lawyer, has one slim file and a sealed envelope. Bode sits apart from the brothers.

MAYA
The legal part is simple.

MALIK
That usually means the opposite.

MAYA
Your father left the Oku family house
and its adjoining land outside Calabar
to the three of you. One undivided gift.

ADE
And if one of us says no?

MAYA
It remains with the family there.
You owe nothing. You may refuse.

She places the sealed envelope between them.

MAYA
This is not legally binding. It is for
you.

Malik opens it. One sheet in Solomon's tight handwriting. He reads silently. His jaw sets.

ADE
You have to use sound.

Malik gives him the page. Ade reads.

ADE
"My sons. I need you to take me home.
All three. Bring my ashes to the river
boundary of the Oku land outside Calabar."

No farewell. No signature.

MALIK
He is dead and still assigning seats.

MAYA
You may say no.

MALIK
Did he make the land conditional on it?

MAYA
No. The ashes are a request. The property
is a choice the three of you make together.
Your uncle agreed to guide you if you go.
That is all the will can usefully say.

She closes her file. Malik walks her out.

INT. SOLOMON'S HOUSE - DINING ROOM - MOMENTS LATER

Ade holds Solomon's letter. Kai has turned the scratched photograph toward Bode.

KAI
The house in this photograph. Is that it?

BODE
Yes.

Kai places the carving beside the tiny brass shape on the veranda wall. Same broad shoulders. Same narrow center.

KAI
And her?

BODE
Our sister.

KAI
She died there?

BODE
She died. The rest belongs in Calabar.

Malik returns. Takes Solomon's letter from Ade.

MALIK
We are not going.

KAI
You decided quickly.

MALIK
Three people crossing an ocean because
a dead man could not speak while he
was alive.

ADE
He said what he wanted.

MALIK
He gave us a location.

ADE
For Dad, that was practically intimacy.

Malik does not smile.

KAI
He hid the carving. He kept this picture
and destroyed her face. Now he wants all
three of us at the house they came from.

MALIK
That is not a pattern. That is an estate.

KAI
It is when everyone refuses the same
part of it.

Bode absorbs that.

MALIK
You want to fly across the world because
people are withholding information?

KAI
I want the silence to stop being the
only thing we inherit.

Malik turns to Bode.

MALIK
Tell him not to go.

BODE
No.

MALIK
You know what is there.

BODE
I know some of what is there.

MALIK
Then decide.

BODE
Solomon asked me to help if you chose.
He did not ask me to choose for you.

Malik stiffens. Kai looks to Ade. Ade gets up, crosses to the refrigerator and opens it. Three mustards. He takes out the grainy one. Stares at it.

ADE
He arranged the room before he left it.

MALIK
What?

ADE
Dad in the middle. Us around him.
I hate that it worked.

MALIK
Then say no.

ADE
If Kai goes alone, we become the brothers
who let him. If two go and one stays,
we become the ones who went and the one
who did not.

MALIK
That is not a reason to cross an ocean.

ADE
It is the only reason I trust.

Silence. Ade sits.

ADE
I vote we go together. We carry him to
the river. We ask our questions. We come
home together.

Kai raises one hand.

KAI
Yes.

Malik looks at both of them. They wait for him. Neither looks away. He unfolds Solomon's letter. Smooths the crease Ade made.

MALIK
We go together.

Kai waits.

MALIK
We stay together.

ADE
That sounded threatening.

MALIK
It was a condition.

ADE
There he is.

The sound of the room gives way to a SEAT BELT CHIME.

PILOT (V.O.)
Cabin crew, prepare for landing in
Calabar.

CUT TO:

# SEQUENCE IV - ARRIVAL

INT. DOMESTIC AIRCRAFT - DESCENDING - AFTERNOON

Green gathers beneath the wing. Water catches the sky between broad seams of land. The brothers look down at a place their father spent thirty years refusing to describe.

The urn remains in its padded case beneath Malik's seat. His shoes bracket it. Across the aisle, Bode watches the ground rise to meet them.

WHEELS STRIKE RUNWAY.

EXT. MARGARET EKPO INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT - ARRIVALS - AFTERNOON

The doors open. Heat arrives like a hand laid flat against the face. Sound follows: Car horns. Names called across traffic. Trolley wheels hitting broken pavement. An argument ending in laughter.

The brothers step out carrying Vancouver in the cut of their clothes. Sweat finds them immediately.

ADE
Canada has been lying about weather.

The airport keeps everyone close enough to negotiate with. A PORTER, twenties, moves toward their luggage.

PORTER
Oga, make I help.

He takes hold of Ade's suitcase before anyone answers. Malik pulls it back.

MALIK
No. Leave it.

The porter keeps one hand on the handle.

PORTER
No worry. I go carry am.

Bode steps beside Malik. He does not raise his voice.

BODE
My brother, leave am. We no need help.

The porter looks at Bode. Releases the handle.

PORTER
No vex, sir.

Bode nods.

BODE
No problem.

The whole exchange takes five seconds. Malik is still holding the suitcase too tightly. Bode takes the trolley.

BODE
Come.

The brothers do.

EXT. CALABAR ROAD - BODE'S VEHICLE - LATER

The city passes in layers. Painted shopfronts. Church signs. School uniforms. Palm shadows sliding across windshields. Red earth appearing wherever pavement gives up. Kai films through the window. People.

A mechanic asleep beneath a lifted car. Two girls sharing earphones. A woman balancing bread on her head while texting. Bode points through the windscreen toward a road disappearing into green.

BODE
Your father used to race bicycle there.

ADE
Dad had a bicycle?

BODE
Your father had a childhood.

KAI
We have not seen evidence.

BODE
He had legs too.

Ade laughs. Malik looks out at the road. For one moment, he tries to place his father on it. Cannot. The city thins. Walls give way to compounds. The air grows greener. Bode turns onto a narrower road.

BODE
Home.

Tires leave asphalt for red earth.

CUT TO:

# SEQUENCE V - HOMECOMING

EXT. OKU FAMILY COMPOUND - LATE AFTERNOON

A broad family compound shaped by additions rather than a single plan. An older central house with deep verandas. A newer concrete wing. Solar panels beside a corrugated roof. Carved doors. Plastic water tanks.

Children's bicycles. Satellite dishes. Laundry moving in the heat. Every part of the compound is in use. The vehicle enters through an open gate. People come out before the engine stops.

COUSIN EYO, 43, practical and quick, opens the rear hatch. Children crowd the brothers until one look from Eyo restores a lane. Then AUNTIE ENO, early sixties, crosses the veranda. She does not hurry.

Everyone else adjusts around her pace. Bode steps forward.

BODE
Mọkọm, Eno.

ENO
Ekọm do.

Eno touches his cheek. Counts the months since she last saw him without asking. Then she turns to the brothers. Malik offers his hand.

ENO
That is all?

MALIK
Good afternoon, Aunty.

ENO
Mọkọm.

MALIK
Mọkọm, Aunty.

ENO
Better.

She ignores the hand and takes his face between both of hers. Turns it toward the light.

ENO
Solomon kept this forehead in Canada.

Malik does not know whether he has been welcomed or examined. Eno releases him. Ade opens his arms.

ADE
I prepared for a hug.

ENO
You people came from Canada and forgot
how to greet?

Ade lowers his arms.

ADE
Mọkọm, Aunty Eno.

He bows his head just enough to make the respect clear without pretending fluency he does not have.

ENO
This one still has mouth.

She pulls him into an embrace. Ade closes his eyes inside it. Only for a second. Eno turns to Kai. He has already removed his camera from between them.

KAI
Mọkọm, Aunty.

ENO
And this one came to inspect us.

KAI
I am just looking.

ENO
Then greet what you are looking at.

She touches his cheek once. Gentler than the sentence. Then she sees the padded black case in Malik's hand. The compound quiets by degrees. Bode takes off his cap.

BODE
We brought him.

Eno approaches the case. She does not open it. She lays her palm on the lid. The gesture is ordinary. The grief is not.

ENO
You took your time, Solomon.

She removes her hand.

ENO
Bring him inside before the heat insults
him. The rest of you - wash. You look
like the airport has eaten you.

INT. OKU FAMILY HOUSE - FRONT ROOM - MOMENTS LATER

The front room carries several generations without arranging them for visitors. Family portraits. School certificates. A charging station crowded with phones.

An old cabinet of carved wood beneath a flat-screen television. The brass urn is placed on a sturdy side table. Malik checks the surface first. Solid. Level. Eno watches him test it.

ENO
If the table survived this family, it
can hold your father.

Malik removes his hand. Children peer through the doorway. Eno turns.

ENO
Give them air.

They disappear. Not far.

INT. OKU FAMILY HOUSE - DINING ROOM - DUSK

Food reaches the table before questions do. Afang soup. Fufu. Rice. Fried plantain. Grilled fish. Water sweating in glass bottles. The brothers sit among relatives whose names arrive faster than memory can keep them.

Eno serves Malik until he says enough. Then adds one more spoon.

MALIK
Aunty, thank you. That is enough.

ENO
You are negotiating with soup.

ADE
He does it with eggs too.

ENO
Tomorrow I will give him eggs. We will
see who wins.

Ade looks at his plate.

ADE
I should warn you, I can cook.

Eno gives him a careful look.

ENO
Confidence is what people use when skill
is not available.

The table erupts. Ade accepts the hit. Eyo points his spoon at Bode.

EYO
Tell them about the mangoes.

BODE
There is nothing to tell.

ENO
Because you helped him.

ADE
Dad stole mangoes?

BODE
Borrowed.

ENO
From trees that did not belong to him.

BODE
The trees recovered.

EYO
He sold them back to the owner.

Malik laughs. He looks as startled as anyone. Covers it with water.

ADE
What else could he do?

Eno thinks.

ENO
At twelve he learned how to boil water.

BODE
Eleven.

ENO
Twelve. For one month he entered the
kitchen asking why everybody was still
working without him.

Ade folds over laughing, one hand braced against the table. He does not check whether anyone follows. Kai smiles. Malik looks toward the urn in the front room.

MALIK
He never told us any of this.

The laughter eases.

ENO
Children do not know their parents were
children. Parents work very hard to keep
it that way.

KAI
Why?

ENO
Because a child can forgive a father.

She looks toward the front room.

ENO
A child does not always forgive a man.

Bode and Eno share a glance. Small. Old. Kai catches it.

MALIK
What happened here?

ENO
Tonight? You arrived. You ate. Your
uncle exaggerated mangoes.

BODE
You accused me first.

ENO
Tomorrow, Bode will show you the land.
After that, you can begin asking the land
questions as if it owes you answers.

KAI
And you?

ENO
I will still be here when you learn the
difference.

She reaches for his plate. Kai protects it.

KAI
I am still eating.

ENO
Good. Canada did not finish you.

The conversation starts again around them. Through the doorway, the urn catches the room light.

INT. OKU FAMILY HOUSE - BROTHERS' ROOM - NIGHT

Three narrow beds. Three mosquito nets tied up for air. Suitcases open on the floor. The room is hot enough to make sleep theoretical. Ade lies on one bed, still smiling at the ceiling.

ADE
Mangoes.

MALIK
Go to sleep.

ADE
He sold stolen mangoes back to the man.

KAI
Allegedly.

ADE
No. That is our father. I finally have
a complete fact.

Malik removes his watch. Sets it beside the bed.

MALIK
You have a story.

ADE
I will take it.

Kai sits with the scratched photograph. He has placed the brass carving beside it.

MALIK
Put those away.

KAI
The object in the background is the same.

MALIK
We established that.

KAI
No one at dinner mentioned her.

ADE
You did not ask.

KAI
They knew I had already asked.

Malik looks at Bode's younger face in the photograph. Then at the missing one between the brothers.

MALIK
Tomorrow.

Kai looks at him.

MALIK
Not as an answer. As a time.

Kai wraps the photograph again. The brothers settle. Outside: Family voices on the veranda. Cutlery being washed. A generator starting two compounds away.

INT. OKU FAMILY HOUSE - BREAKFAST AREA - MORNING

Morning arrives already loud. Eggs. Fried plantain. Bread. Tea. The Afang soup from last night, because Eno does not believe good food must respect the clock.

ENO
Emesiere.

The brothers answer with varying confidence.

BROTHERS
Emesiere nde.

Eno nods. Malik eats the eggs. She watches.

ENO
Well?

MALIK
They are very good.

ENO
Not "very good." Who won?

Malik surrenders one inch.

MALIK
The eggs.

Eno nods. Order restored. Bode enters dressed for the land. Light shirt. Sturdy shoes. A folded map he does not need. Malik notices the map.

BODE
We leave in twenty minutes.

ADE
Now he speaks your language.

BODE
The river path is long. We will show you
the boundaries first. If the weather
holds, we continue to the water.

Malik looks toward the urn in the front room.

MALIK
Today?

BODE
Today we walk. At the river, you decide
if today is the day.

The brothers finish eating.

CUT TO:

# SEQUENCE VI - THE LAND AND THE SHRINE

EXT. OKU FAMILY COMPOUND - MORNING

Eyo secures water and food in a canvas pack. The brass urn remains inside its padded case. Malik lifts it. Ade reaches for one handle. Malik lets him. Together, they carry Solomon through the gate.

Eno stands on the veranda.

ENO
Bring everybody back before dark.

ADE
No instruction for the dead?

ENO
He has ignored enough instructions.

Bode almost smiles. The four men follow a red-earth path into the family land.

EXT. OKU FAMILY LAND - LATER

The compound disappears behind green. The land is not untouched. It has been worked, abandoned, reclaimed and worked again. Cassava plots. Palm stands. Old drainage cuts softened by rain.

New survey stakes beside boundary stones older than anyone present. Bode stops at the first stone. Three shallow cuts cross its face.

BODE
From here to the river bend. Then east
to the old road.

Malik studies the folded map.

MALIK
The title says forty-two hectares.

BODE
The title learned the land later.

Malik looks up. Bode points.

BODE
That silk-cotton tree was already old
when your grandfather was born.

ADE
Does the tree have paperwork?

BODE
Better witnesses.

They continue. Kai photographs the stone. The three cuts converge around a shallow hollow. He takes the brass carving from his camera bag and holds it beside the mark. The angles differ. Both hollows sit slightly off-center.

KAI
Uncle Bode.

Bode looks from one mark to the other.

BODE
It marks Oku land.

KAI
And the carving?

BODE
It came from here.

KAI
Was it hers?

Bode looks at the carving.

BODE
Put it away.

Kai wraps the carving and returns it to his bag. They walk.

EXT. OLD PALM TRACK - LATER

The path narrows beneath a layered canopy. Heat becomes wet pressure. The urn passes from Malik and Ade to Malik and Bode. Then to Ade alone for a short rise. Each transfer is careful. No ceremony. Practice.

Bode points to a tree bent low across the path.

BODE
Solomon planted that after our mother
said nothing useful would grow where
he put it.

ADE
Spite farming.

BODE
Your father's most reliable crop.

The tree is enormous now. Malik touches its trunk as he passes. Farther on, the path divides around a washout. Bode stops the group.

BODE
From here, stay on the path I take.

ADE
You say that like we have been freelancing.

BODE
Sound travels badly here. Water bends it.
Trees throw it back. If you hear one of
us, look for us before you follow.

Kai studies the two paths.

BODE
And do not believe everything you think
you see. Distance changes quickly under
these trees.

Bode takes the left fork. The others follow.

EXT. BOUNDARY PATH - LATER

The boundary stones return at no regular distance. Each one stands on the right side of the path.

A fallen limb has peeled vines from the slope to Kai's left. Beneath them: An older stone carrying the same three cuts. Facing downhill.

Kai raises his camera. Ahead, Malik and Ade negotiate the urn over a fallen trunk. Bode watches their footing.

Kai steps off the path to frame the exposed stone.

EXT. SLOPE ABOVE THE RAVINE - CONTINUOUS

He takes two careful steps. Wet leaves shear away beneath his shoe. The slope gives. Kai slides, camera clutched to his chest. His free hand catches a root. The root tears loose.

Kai drops into the ravine.

EXT. HIDDEN SHRINE - CONTINUOUS

He lands hard enough to empty his lungs. For several seconds: Mud. Breath. Pain. Kai checks the camera. Unbroken. One scraped palm.

The exposed boundary stone is not freestanding. It is the upper corner of a SHRINE.

Stone and tree have grown into one body. The masonry rises from the ravine wall, soft at the edges from age. Roots enter through old seams and emerge as carved lines. Some roots protect it.

Others appear to hold it shut. At its center: A narrow recess covered by a small slab of wood. The wood is bound to the stone with faded RED THREAD.

Pale grooves circle the wood at different heights beneath the thread. Earlier bindings. Kai remains where he fell. He looks up the slope. The family is no longer visible. Movement somewhere above. No words he can make out.

Kai takes the carving from his camera bag. The roots describe the same three cuts around a hollow. He holds the carving beside them. Photographs both.

Kai approaches. He touches the wood. Dry beneath the damp air. The red thread crosses itself in a practiced knot. One loop can be loosened without cutting.

Kai works a fingertip beneath the loop. The thread resists. He stops. Looks back toward the slope. Pulls again.

The old thread snaps -- a dry little sound. The forest continues around him. Insects. Birds. Leaves rubbing in the upper air. Kai catches the wooden cover before it falls.

Behind it, a recess blackened by age. Inside: A BRASS TALISMAN. Palm-sized. Green at the edges. Its design holds the same three converging lines. Here, the hollow at their center is filled.

Kai studies where it sits. Photographs it. Then removes it with two fingers.

The moment the brass clears the recess --

Insects. Birds. The upper leaves.

Gone.

The talisman pulls heat from Kai's fingers.

Another PALM beneath his. Older. Red thread cutting across both hands.

River water at his chest.

Somewhere below --

BRASS STRIKES STONE.

Kai drops to one knee. His jaw locks against a cry. The talisman remains in his fist. The empty recess waits at eye level.

His free hand moves toward it. Stops.

The ground answers with one DEEP BEAT. Impact through root and stone. Kai feels it in his teeth. High above, leaves turn their pale undersides toward the ravine.

MALIK (O.S.)
Kai!

Kai raises the talisman toward the recess. Holds it one inch from where it sat.

MALIK (O.S.)
Kai!

Kai closes his hand. Slips the talisman into his camera bag.

At the base of the shrine, something moves. A BLACK SPIDER emerges from the seam between root and stone. Small. Unhurried. It crosses the snapped red thread.

Stops on the broken loop.

BODE (O.S.)
Kai!

Bode's voice cracks on the name. Kai looks toward the slope. Then back at the shrine. The spider begins to follow the broken thread toward open ground.

CUT TO BLACK.

# END OF ACT I
